ACRED HISTORY: A FEW INTERESTING CASES -- tCOUNT YOUR BLESSINGS: JEWISH MOURNING RITUALS DURING THE SPRING SEASON -- tCOMIC INTERLUDE -- tMAKING FISH FOR SHABBAT (YOMA 75A) -- tMEDIEVAL INTERPRETATION -- tEMBARRASSMENT AS A MEANS OF EMBRACING AUTHORIAL INTENT -- tTHE DOUBLE PATH: THE TWO LAYERS OF THINKING AND THE TWOFOLD NATURE OF KNOWLEDGE IN THE WORKS OF SAADYA GAON -- t410 EMBARRASSMENT AS A CREATIVE FORCE IN MAIMONIDES’ META-HALAKHIC ENUMERATION OF THE 613 COMMANDMENTS -- tTEACHING PHILOSOPHY TO THE MULTITUDE: AN INTRODUCTION TO THE EDUCATIONAL THEORY OF NISSIM BEN MOSHE OF MARSEILLES -- tMODERN -- tRABBI NATAN SLIFKIN ON SCIENCE AND TORAH: THE EVOLUTION OF A SEARCH FOR TRUTH -- tMAPPING ALTERNATE TEXTS OF GENDER DIFFERENCE -- tHOW CAN THEY BE BETTER THAN US? EMBARRASSMENT AND LEGISLATION -- t“SUCH THINGS HAVE NEVER BEEN HEARD OF”: JEWISH INTELLECTUALS AND HASIDIC MIRACLES -- t“CHOSENNESS” -- tDURÉE, DEVEKUTH, & RE-EMBRACING THE GODLOVER: INVOLUTION OF UNIO MYSTICA VIA COLLOCATIVE HOMOSEXUELITY -- tENVIRONMENTAL EMBARRASSMENT: GENESIS 1:26-28 VS. GENESIS 2:15 -- tAFTERWORD -- tVIXENS DISTURBING VINEYARDS: WHY FOX’S EMBRACEMENT OF SCRIPTURES CAN BE EMBARRASSING -- tHEBREW CONTRIBUTIONS -- tהעתקה עברית של רִסאלת אלחאתִמי: השוואה בין אמרות המיוחסות לאריסטו לבין בתי שיר למֻתַנבִַּי -- tאשת יפת תואר בספרי ובפרשנות הקדומה -- t׳׳…וקצתה את כפה לא תחוס עינך׳׳ (דברים כה, יב) -- tבין חכמים לציבור: כיצד נוצרה ההלכה שבתורה שבעל פה0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmbarrassment and embracement are two moments in the reading, misreading and re-reading of scriptures, defined broadly to include both canonical and non-canonical texts. Despite what Harold Bloom calls our "belatedness" in this process, every reading community has its way of confronting that moment of embarrassment so as to re-embrace or reject its implications. These implications are especially strong in religious cultures with a nomian tradition. By entering into that very tension between what Fox calls embarrassment and re-embracement, every reader recognizes the anxiety of a narrative's influence upon a community. Papers dealing with different aspects of this phenomenon are part of a festschrift honoring Professor Harry Fox (LeBeit Yoreh) the originator of this seminal idea in the transmission of texts. Contributors include such scholars as Yaakov Elman, Simcha Fishbane, the late Chana Safrai and Tirzah Meacham as well as many students, colleagues and friends of Professor Fox.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmbarrassment. 0aGentiles in rabbinical literature. 0aGentiles in the Old Testament. 0aJewish ethics. 0aJudaismxRelations. 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aAncselovits, Elisha S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasser, Herbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClenman, Laliv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkin, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElman, Pearl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElman, Yaakov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishbane, Simcha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedberg, Albert Dov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazer, Aubrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazer, Aubrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazer, Aubrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGo